* Press on into the swamp = Thank her and refuse, trusting your own sense of direction over the charity of a woman who lives where nothing should.
  You barely make it a dozen yards before the shack unfolds impossible legs from beneath its stilts and comes crashing after you through the black water, the hermit's laughter echoing across the fen like a crow's cry. You run until your lungs burn and the darkness is complete, finally collapsing in some nameless hollow where the cypress roots offer meager shelter. By the time you manage a fire, you have no idea which way leads forward—only that the smoke behind you has long since vanished, and with it, any sense of where you've been.
